So far, we have learned about resume <strong>headings</strong> and <strong>objective statements</strong>. How much do you remember from last lesson?

________________________________________________________________________________

Now that you are experts on the first two parts of a resume, let’s look at the third:

<span style="text-decoration: underline;"><strong>Education<img class="wp-image-44147 alignright" src="http://p2i.pyd.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/01/Graduation-Cap-Education-resumes-2b.png" alt="graduation-cap-education-resumes-2b" width="350" height="237" /></strong></span><span style="text-decoration: underline;"><strong>
</strong></span>

1. Heading (Personal Information)

2. Objective Statement

<strong>3. Education</strong>

4. Work Experience

5. Volunteer Experience

6. Skills

7. Optional Sections

The education section of a resume tells an employer about your past experience in school. This is important because certain jobs may require a type of degree, and employers may be impressed by a candidate that is a good student.

<img class="alignnone wp-image-44123" src="http://p2i.pyd.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/01/Education-Definition-resumes-2b-1000x233.png" alt="education-definition-resumes-2b" width="750" height="175" />

Take a look at the resume on the next page to see one example of how this looks!

<img class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-44221" src="http://p2i.pyd.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/01/Sample-Resume-Education-resumes-2b-830x1000.png" alt="sample-resume-education-resumes-2b" width="830" height="1000" />

<strong>Note: </strong>If you have been out of school and working for a long time, it may make more sense to put the “work experience” section ahead of education.

<strong> </strong>

<strong>What information should go in an Education section?</strong>
<ul>
 	<li>Name of all high schools and colleges you have attended</li>
 	<li>City and state of each school</li>
 	<li>Type of degree you received (high school diploma or GED count!)</li>
 	<li>Month and year that you graduated or will graduate from each school</li>
</ul>
<em>Optional information</em>
<ul>
 	<li><em>GPA – only include your GPA if you are proud of it!</em></li>
 	<li><em>Honors – if you do not have a separate resume section for “Honors” or “Awards”, you can include <strong>academic</strong> achievements here.</em></li>
 	<li><em>Examples of this are “honor roll” or “dean’s high honors”</em></li>
</ul>
<img class="alignnone wp-image-44225" src="http://p2i.pyd.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/01/Education-Chronological-Order-resumes-2b-1000x522.png" alt="education-chronological-order-resumes-2b" width="677" height="354" />

