________________________________________________________________________________

<strong><u>Work Experience</u></strong>
<ol>
 	<li>Heading (Personal Information)</li>
 	<li>Objective Statement</li>
 	<li>Education</li>
 	<li><strong>Work Experience</strong></li>
 	<li>Volunteer Experience</li>
 	<li>Skills</li>
 	<li>Optional Sections</li>
</ol>
The work experience section is the other very important part of your resume, because employers want to know what skills, experience, and knowledge you can bring to their workplace!

<img class="alignnone wp-image-44231" src="http://p2i.pyd.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/01/Work-Experience-Definition-resumes-2b-1000x203.png" alt="work-experience-definition-resumes-2b" width="750" height="152" />

What information should you include in the work experience section?
<ul>
 	<li>Name of previous company or employer</li>
 	<li>Employer location (city and state)</li>
 	<li>Your job title</li>
 	<li>Months and years of employment</li>
 	<li>Your duties and accomplishments at that job</li>
</ul>
The words you use to describe your responsibilities are very important!

Even if you mastered a skill that you think will not help you in your next job, try to think about what transferrable skills were involved.

<img class="alignnone wp-image-44234" src="http://p2i.pyd.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/01/Transferable-Skills-Definition-resumes-2b-1000x224.png" alt="transferable-skills-definition-resumes-2b" width="750" height="168" />

<strong>TRANSFERRABLE SKILLS  </strong>

The things you do EVERY DAY at work that can be applied to other types of jobs.

